<subSubSection id="C35436B80B3EFFF3FF18BE31928DACCC" pageId="47" pageNumber="72" type="description">
<paragraph id="8BF165330B3EFFF3FF18BE31928DACCC" blockId="47.[136,1452,806,1013]" pageId="47" pageNumber="72">
<emphasis id="B93AB9210B3EFFF3FF18BE3196B0AC78" bold="true" box="[136,241,806,832]" pageId="47" pageNumber="72">Notes:â€”</emphasis>
We only saw 
<taxonomicName id="4C4E1EB00B3EFFF3FE02BE3197BDAC78" box="[402,508,806,832]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Cactaceae" genus="Consolea" kingdom="Plantae" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="47" pageNumber="72" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B93AB9210B3EFFF3FE02BE3197BDAC78" box="[402,508,806,832]" italics="true" pageId="47" pageNumber="72">Consolea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
growing as a garden ornamental on 
<collectingCountry id="F35925A30B3EFFF3FC3EBE319250AC78" box="[942,1041,806,832]" name="Grenada" pageId="47" pageNumber="72">Grenada</collectingCountry>
. The plants had spineless pads and proliferating and spineless flower and fruit cladodes. We identified this as 
<taxonomicName id="4C4E1EB00B3EFFF3FC47BE5D93EAAC5C" authority="Lemaire (1862: 174)" authorityName="Lemaire" authorityPageNumber="174" authorityYear="1862" box="[983,1451,842,868]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Cactaceae" genus="Consolea" kingdom="Plantae" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="47" pageNumber="72" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="rubescens">
<emphasis id="B93AB9210B3EFFF3FC47BE5D92F8AC5C" box="[983,1209,842,868]" italics="true" pageId="47" pageNumber="72">Consolea rubescens</emphasis>
Lemaire (1862: 174)
</taxonomicName>
because the name is commonly applied to this spineless species, which is native to the northern Lesser Antilles. There is an interesting specimen at K (barcode K000100705) collected in 1896 by Waby, which has large spiny pads. The specimen is annotated as 
<taxonomicName id="4C4E1EB00B3EFFF3FE33BEA19437ACE8" box="[419,630,950,976]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Cactaceae" genus="Opuntia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="47" pageNumber="72" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="rubescens">
<emphasis id="B93AB9210B3EFFF3FE33BEA19437ACE8" box="[419,630,950,976]" italics="true" pageId="47" pageNumber="72">Opuntia rubescens</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
but is probably a different 
<taxonomicName id="4C4E1EB00B3EFFF3FC34BEA19224ACE8" box="[932,1125,950,976]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Cactaceae" genus="Consolea" kingdom="Plantae" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="47" pageNumber="72" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="undetermined">
<emphasis id="B93AB9210B3EFFF3FC34BEA1924FACE8" box="[932,1038,950,976]" italics="true" pageId="47" pageNumber="72">Consolea</emphasis>
species
</taxonomicName>
in cultivation in 
<collectingCountry id="F35925A30B3EFFF3FAB3BEA193D1ACE8" box="[1315,1424,950,976]" name="Barbados" pageId="47" pageNumber="72">Barbados</collectingCountry>
. It is unlikely to be native there as neither 
<bibRefCitation id="EFDF18C20B3EFFF3FDD0BECD94A6ACCD" author="Hughes, G." box="[576,743,986,1013]" pageId="47" pageNumber="72" refId="ref17166" refString="Hughes, G. (1750) The Natural History of Barbados. Published by the author, London, 314 pp. https: // doi. org / 10.5962 / bhl. title. 47069" type="book" year="1750">Hughes (1750)</bibRefCitation>
nor 
<bibRefCitation id="EFDF18C20B3EFFF3FC8BBECD9594ACCC" author="Maycock, J. D." box="[795,981,986,1012]" pageId="47" pageNumber="72" refId="ref17739" refString="Maycock, J. D. (1830) Flora Barbadensis. James Ridgway, London, 446 pp." type="book" year="1830">Maycock (1830)</bibRefCitation>
mention such a plant.
</paragraph>
